# File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)

## Objective
When an attacker breaches a system, one of the first things they might do is:
- Modify a configuration file
- Change a password file
- Replace a program with malware
- Delete important logs
- Create a malicious script

File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) watches important files/folders and alerts on **creation, modification, deletion, or renaming**.

## Setup
By default, Wazuh only monitors predefined directories (system folders, etc.) — not every folder on Windows. Since `C:\SOC-Lab` was a new custom folder, it had to be added explicitly to the agent's `<syscheck>` configuration before FIM would report on it.

**Steps taken:**
1. Opened Notepad **as Administrator**.
2. Opened the Wazuh agent's `ossec.conf`.
3. Located the `<syscheck>` section.
4. Added `C:\SOC-Lab` as a monitored directory (realtime).
5. Saved the file.
6. Restarted the Wazuh Agent: `Restart-Service WazuhSvc`

## Commands Run

| # | Command | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path C:\SOC-Lab -Force` | Creates the monitored folder |
| 2 | `New-Item -ItemType File -Path C:\SOC-Lab\test.txt -Force` | Creates an empty test file |
| 3 | `Set-Content C:\SOC-Lab\test.txt "Hello Wazuh"` | Writes initial content |
| 4 | `Set-Content C:\SOC-Lab\test.txt "Hello Wazuh - Modified"` | Modifies the file — should trigger a modification event |
| 5 | `Remove-Item C:\SOC-Lab\test.txt` | Deletes the file — should trigger a "file deleted" event |

## Investigation — Wazuh Alert

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| agent.name | Windows11 |
| full_log | `File 'c:\soc-lab\test.txt' deleted Mode: realtime` |
| rule.description | File deleted. |
| rule.id | 553 |
| rule.level | 7 |
| syscheck.path | c:\soc-lab\test.txt |
| syscheck.md5_after | 91967a60200e895f085a805a3933a303 |
| syscheck.sha256_after | ae2697b447a683713584db0d9f18422485164248abbea2c5de3a20886f688b30 |
| timestamp | Jul 6, 2026 @ 17:21:09.221 |

Related rule IDs observed during this test: **550** (integrity checksum changed), **554** (file added to the system), **553** (file deleted).

## Takeaway
FIM only works on directories explicitly configured in `<syscheck>` — a folder invisible to Wazuh generates zero alerts even if heavily tampered with. Configuration scope directly determines detection coverage.
